  <content>
    <section class="learning-objectives" id="sect-00009"><title>Learning Outcomes</title>
      <para id="para-00002">By the end of this section, you will be able to:</para>
      <list id="list-00001">
        <item>Define cultural and linguistic competence.</item>
        <item>Explain the basic concepts of culturally competent nursing care.</item>
        <item>Discuss the relationship between cultural competence and health outcomes.</item>
        <item>Identify how cultural humility and cultural awareness affect nursing care.</item>
        <item>Describe how valuing and respecting diversity affect health care.</item>
      </list></section>
      <para id="para-00001">Like culture, cultural competence is a dynamic process. Although there are many definitions of <term id="term-00001">cultural competence</term>, this chapter will utilize the one adopted by the American Association of Colleges of Nursing (AACN): “cultural competence encompasses the attitudes, knowledge, and skills necessary for providing quality care to diverse populations” (AACN, 2008). The process of developing cultural competence involves individuals and organizations working to understand, respect, and value a person’s or group’s unique background, identity, and characteristics. Greater cultural competence improves a nurse’s ability to understand, communicate with, and effectively provide care to individuals from diverse cultural backgrounds.</para>
    <para id="para-00003">
      Cultural competence does not mean knowing everything about every culture. With hundreds, perhaps thousands, of cultures around the world, all of them continually changing, such knowledge would be impossible. Instead, cultural competence occurs along a continuum, beginning with the first exploration of one’s own attitudes, beliefs, and values and continuing through a reflective process with the aim of providing <term id="term-00002">culturally congruent care</term>, or care that aligns with a client’s or population’s health beliefs and behaviors.
    </para>
    <para id="para-00004">
      Like cultural competence, <term id="term-00003">linguistic competence</term> also exists along a continuum, and, like cultural competence, it is not based on comprehensive knowledge. Rather, it consists of acquiring the knowledge, attitudes, and skills that enable nurses to care and advocate for clients who communicate in a language other than the one most commonly spoken and/or understood in the service setting.
    </para>
    <section id="sect-00001">
      <title>The Value of Culturally Competent Nursing</title>
      <para id="para-00005">The latest research in nursing emphasizes the importance of improving cultural competence to provide culturally congruent care (Im &amp; Chee, 2021). Cultural congruence involves recognizing and respecting cultural preferences and needs, as well as being able to provide optimal care tailored to an individual or population. Recognizing the ways that culture can influence client beliefs and behaviors, as well as the ways in which an individual’s cultural background affects their health care experiences, enables nurses to improve client outcomes, increase client satisfaction, and reduce <term id="term-00004">health inequities</term>. Studies have shown that when nurses are culturally competent, they demonstrate more empathy, communicate more effectively, and provide better client education (Umanzor &amp; Arcaute-Gonzalex, 2019). These skills improve client outcomes, increase satisfaction, and reduce health inequities, which are differences in health resources or health status based on social factors. In addition, nurses who strive to become culturally competent can more readily navigate challenging situations when providing care for diverse populations. They are more likely to be aware of the potential biases that can come into play when delivering care and better able to take steps to minimize those biases. Building relationships of trust between communities and health care professionals can help ensure that individuals receive the appropriate care they need, regardless of their cultural origins.
      </para>

    <section id="sect-00002">
      <title>Culturally Congruent Care</title>
      <para id="para-00006">When nurses practice cultural competence, they aim to provide culturally congruent care. Culturally congruent care is consistent with the cultural beliefs, values, and practices of the client and tailored to their cultural needs. For example, a nurse wishes to provide culturally congruent care for a client with diabetes who has stated that they frequently consult with a traditional healer about their dietary choices. To provide culturally congruent care, the nurse takes the client’s beliefs and practices into account, perhaps consulting with a traditional practitioner to incorporate culturally appropriate foods into the client's care plan. The nurse can the client with education about their dietary choices and encourage them to continue incorporating healthy practices that are congruent with their culture.</para>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00003">
      <title>Reducing Health Inequities</title>
      <para id="para-00007">Cultural competence reduces health inequities by increasing awareness and understanding of the cultural beliefs, values, and practices of diverse populations. Cultural competence promotes respect and understanding between nurses and clients, which can bridge differences in cultural backgrounds. Nurses who respect and understand the cultural beliefs and values of a client are better prepared to provide care that is consistent with the client's cultural expectations and practices. This can help to reduce health inequities, as the client is more likely to collaborate with health care providers and to understand and follow the recommended care plan, regardless of their background or circumstances.</para>
      <para id="para-00008">Cultural competence reduces barriers and increases access to care. For example, a nurse who coordinates <term id="term-00005">translation</term> for clients who speak another language helps those clients access needed services and health-related information (Foronda &amp; Baptiste, 2022). When practicing cultural competence, nurses provide care that is tailored to the cultural needs of clients, increasing access for underserved and marginalized populations.</para>

      <note class="health-alert" id="note-00001">
        <title>The Educational Roots of Health Inequities</title>
        <para id="para-00009">The educational roots of health inequities result from institutional and systemic biases in policies that separate individuals into either resource-rich or resource-poor neighborhoods as these neighborhoods dictate school access. This separation into resource-rich or poor neighborhoods is principally based on socioeconomic position and race resulting in wide health disparities in life expectancy and health outcomes as education is a major factor in shaping the course of an individual’s life.</para>
        <para id="para-00010">Source:  National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine.  (2017). Communities in Action: Pathways to Health Equity.  National Academies Press. Retrieved from The Root Causes of Health Inequity - Communities in Action - NCBI Bookshelf (nih.gov)</para>
      </note>

      <para id="para-00011">Cultural competence also informs nurses about the <term id="term-00006">social determinants of health (SDOH)</term>, which are the conditions in which people are born, grow, live, work, and age (<link target-id="pophealth_fig_23_01_002"/>). As discussed in Social Determinants of Health, these conditions include factors such as income, education, housing, employment, and access to health care, and they can create significant health inequities (Office of Disease Prevention and Health Promotion [ODPHP], n.d.). For example, some communities with high levels of <term id="term-00007">poverty</term> are considered “<term id="term-00008">food deserts</term>,” areas where access to affordable and nutritious food is limited or nonexistent. This can be due to a lack of grocery stores in the area, inadequate transportation options, and low-income levels that make it difficult for residents to afford healthy food. Food deserts are a serious public health concern because they can contribute to a number of health problems, including obesity, diabetes, and heart disease. People living in food deserts are often forced to rely on convenience stores and fast-food restaurants, which tend to offer unhealthy food options that are high in calories, fat, and sodium, resulting in a higher prevalence of chronic diseases. A nurse who is aware of the impact of a food desert on the local community can advocate for the increased availability of nutritious foods in places such as corner stores, promote the incorporation of healthy foods into school meals, and provide education to help people find healthy food and make healthier choices.</para>

