      </figure>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00004">
      <title>Improving Health Outcomes</title>
      <para id="para-00012">Culturally competent nurses better understand and respond to their clients’ needs. They recognize and respect cultural differences, remain cognizant of personal and structural biases, and provide <term id="term-00009">culturally sensitive care</term>. By understanding the unique cultural needs of their clients, nurses can provide more effective and personalized care, which can lead to improved health outcomes.</para>
      <para id="para-00013">As nurses develop their cultural competence, they attain a better understanding of the wide variety of cultures, values, beliefs, practices, and health care needs among different groups. Cultural competence supports the delivery of <term id="term-00010">culturally responsive care</term>, the process of providing care to individuals or populations that fully takes into consideration their cultural backgrounds, values, and preferences. This type of care goes beyond being sensitive to culture; it involves actively ensuring that all aspects of health care are tailored to address the needs and beliefs of a specific population (Hemmings et al., 2016). By providing care consistent with a client’s or group’s specific cultural needs and expectations, nurses foster an understanding and respectful environment, promoting trust and client collaboration. Cultural and linguistic competence also facilitates better communication between nurses and clients, improved health management, increased adherence to treatment plans, and increased client satisfaction. In turn, clients are encouraged to engage with their care, leading to improved health outcomes.</para>

      <note class="culture-conversations" id="note-00002">
        <title>What Is Cultural Competence?</title>
        <para id="para-00014">In the <term id="term-00011">Kentucky Inclusive Health Collaborative</term> video “<link url="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vHePY3J5wJs">Cultural Competency in Health</link>,” people speak about the different ways they identify themselves and how they feel health care providers’ perceptions of them affect the care they receive.</para>
        <para id="para-00015">Watch the video, and then respond to the questions below.</para>
        <media alt="Alt text here.">
          <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vHePY3J5wJs"/>
        </media>
        <list list-type="enumerated" id="list-00002">
          <item>What are the different terms you use to describe your identity?</item>
          <item>How may others’ perceptions of your identity affect the health care you receive?</item>
          <item>What can you do to increase your cultural competency as a nurse?</item>
          <item>What effect does your level of cultural competency have on your clients?</item>
        </list>
      </note>
    </section>
  </section>
  <section id="sect-00005">
    <title>Attitudes, Skills, and Knowledge</title>
    <para id="para-00016">The AACN definition of cultural competence is, above all, a call to action: It sets nurses the task of building the attitudes, skills, and knowledge necessary to provide quality care. What are those attitudes, skills, and knowledge?</para>
    <para id="para-00017">An open, non-judgmental attitude is essential to providing culturally competent care. A culturally competent nurse displays interest in learning about other beliefs and practices, a willingness to engage in dialogue that encourages learning and mutual respect, motivation to challenge assumptions and biases, a commitment to equity and inclusion, and a desire to help create a safe space for everyone. Culturally competent attitudes also include a positive approach to diversity, valuing and respecting cultural differences, and not discriminating against individuals on the basis of culture.</para>
    <para id="para-00018">An attitude critical to cultural competence is <term id="term-00012">cultural humility</term>, which entails acknowledging, respecting, and valuing cultural differences by taking responsibility for one’s own perceptions and ideas. When an individual has cultural humility, they have a deep respect for all cultures as well a desire to learn more and to understand different people’s perspectives. This approach emphasizes self-reflection, open communication, and collaboration across diverse populations. Having humility, or being humble about one’s beliefs and understanding that they are not the best or only way, also involves being aware of one’s own biases and limitations, and understanding that these can influence how one interacts with people from different cultural backgrounds.</para>
    <para id="para-00019">Among the many skills required to provide culturally competent care, a few key skills should be part of every nurse’s toolkit. Critical thinking skills are needed to identify and analyze policies, structures, and practices that are oppressive or that disadvantage certain individuals or groups. Linguistic competence is necessary so that nurses can communicate effectively with people from different backgrounds, listening empathetically and openly. The ability to adapt to new cultural environments and navigate unfamiliar situations is essential.</para>
    <para id="para-00020">As mentioned above, nurses do not need to possess knowledge of every culture they interact with. In the process of developing cultural competence, nurses seek <term id="term-00013">cultural awareness</term>. In nursing, cultural awareness is defined as “the process of understanding and respecting the beliefs, customs, languages, and values of clients from diverse cultures” (Giger &amp; Davidhizar, 2002; Giger &amp; Davidhizar, 2008). It involves recognizing that culture shapes perspectives and experiences and influences the way people express themselves, and it acknowledges that cultural norms may differ from those most often found in conventional health care settings. Cultural awareness also involves becoming knowledgeable about one's own cultural group and identifying how one's own background may influence their perspectives and behaviors, and how this may impact their interactions with people from other cultures. Cultural awareness involves the ability to recognize and appreciate individual differences and treat them with respect. It is rooted in values such as openness, respect, fairness, and mutual understanding.</para>
    <section id="sect-00006">
      <title>Valuing and Respecting Diversity</title>
      <para id="para-00021">In valuing diversity, the nurse recognizes and appreciates the unique characteristics, backgrounds, experiences, and perspectives of individuals and groups. Individuals and groups may be diverse in numerous ways, including their culture, race, ethnicity, religion, gender, sexual orientation, age, and ability. Valuing diversity involves not only recognizing that everyone is unique, and that this diversity is a valuable aspect of society, but also treating all individuals with respect and without discrimination. It involves being open to learning from, and collaborating with, people from diverse backgrounds. Valuing diversity can foster a more inclusive and welcoming environment, and it can lead to better outcomes for both individuals and organizations.</para>
      <para id="para-00022">Valuing and respecting diversity begins with acknowledging and recognizing the unique backgrounds, experiences, and perspectives of clients and colleagues. This can include learning about the wide variations found in cultural health beliefs and practices, engaging with people from different backgrounds and cultures, and treating all clients with respect and compassion. Effective communication is also critical, as is being open-minded and willing to learn from others. Nurses who advocate for diversity and inclusion in the workplace and recognize and challenge any personal biases or stereotypes that may impact their interactions with others can foster a more inclusive and nurturing environment for their clients, colleagues, communities, and organizations.</para>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00007">
      <title>Understanding Cultural Identity</title>
      <para id="para-00023"><term id="term-00014">Cultural identity</term>is the unique combination of beliefs, values, attitudes, behaviors, customs, practices, experiences, and language that make up an individual's sense of belonging to a particular group or culture. A person’s cultural identity encompasses who they are and how they fit into society, as well as their larger context within the human experience. It is an important aspect of a person's self-concept, and it can change throughout a person’s lifetime. It includes the ways in which one’s beliefs, perspectives, traditions, practices, and values are shaped by the culture, or cultures, to which they belong. Cultural identity creates belonging, connecting individuals with a community and to shared experiences and traditions with others who have a similar background. It can be influenced by external factors such as <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00015">migration</term>, <term class="no-class" id="term-00016">globalization</term>, and <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00017">colonization</term>.</para>

      <note class="case-reflection" id="note-00003">
        <para id="para-00024">Read the following scenario and reflect on the questions that follow.</para>
          <para id="para-00025">Cory, a community health nurse introduced at the start of this chapter, is meeting another new client in the clinic today. Faiza is a married 28-year-old female who is trying to establish primary and obstetric care. Faiza is scheduled to meet with Nurse Cory to assist her in arranging for appropriate and timely care and to assess whether she needs other health-related resources. Informed that his client has arrived, Nurse Cory goes to the waiting room and calls Faiza’s name. A man rises from his seat, and only then does the young woman wearing a hijab head covering who was seated beside him move her head and stand. She walks behind the man to the front of the room where Nurse Cory is waiting. The man says, “She is Faiza.” Faiza does not look directly at Nurse Cory. Nurse Cory reaches his hand out to Faiza and says, “Hi, my name is Cory, and I’m the nurse you’re seeing today; nice to meet you.” Faiza does not look up and does not take Cory’s hand. She says nothing and takes a small step backward. The man, who appears to be upset, says, “She needs a woman nurse.”</para>
          <list list-type="enumerated" id="list-00003">
            <item>Why do you think the man with Faiza requests a female nurse?</item>
            <item>Does anything about this scenario make you uncomfortable?</item>
            <item>How should Nurse Cory respond?</item>
            <item>What is the significance of the client’s lack of eye contact and avoidance of shaking hands?</item>
            <item>If the clinic cannot provide this client with a female nurse, how should Nurse Cory proceed?</item>
            <item>From the beginning, do you think Nurse Cory should have done anything differently?</item>
          </list>
          <para id="para-00026">SUGGESTED RESOURCE<newline/>Attum, B., Hafiz, S., Malik, A., &amp; Shamoon, Z. (2022). <emphasis effect="italics">Cultural competence in the care of Muslim patients and their families</emphasis>. StatPearls, CC BY-NC-ND 4.0. Retrieved from <link url="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499933/">Cultural Competence in the Care of Muslim Patients and Their Families - StatPearls - NCBI Bookshelf (nih.gov)</link>.</para>
        </note>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00008">
      <title>Identifying Personal Values and Beliefs</title>
      <para id="para-00027">An important first step in the cultural competence process is to develop an understanding of one’s own values and beliefs. This begins with an examination of one’s own life experiences, family background, cultural traditions, religious beliefs, health practices, and personal preferences. It is also important to look at how these values have changed over time, and how they influence the way a nurse interacts with others, including clients, nurse colleagues, and other health care professionals. Additionally, nurses need to examine their own biases to ensure that they are not perpetuating any stereotypes or prejudices when providing care. This process will be covered in more detail in the next section.</para>
    </section>
  </section>

